    "response": "Step 1: Base case \\(n=1\\): LHS = \\(\\frac{(m+1)!}{(m-1)!} = (m+1)m = m(m+1)\\); RHS = \\(\\prod_{i=1}^{1}(m^2+m-i^2+i) = m^2+m-1+1 = m^2+m = m(m+1)\\). So base case holds.\n\nStep 2: Inductive hypothesis: Assume for some integer \\(k \\ge 1\\), \\(\\frac{(m+k)!}{(m-k)!} = \\prod_{i=1}^{k}(m^2+m-i^2+i)\\) for all \\(m \\ge k\\).\n\nStep 3: For \\(n = k+1\\), LHS = \\(\\frac{(m+k+1)!}{(m-k-1)!}\\). Rewrite using factorial properties: \\(\\frac{(m+k+1)!}{(m-k-1)!} = (m-k)(m+k+1) \\cdot \\frac{(m+k)!}{(m-k)!}\\) because \\((m-k-1)! = \\frac{(m-k)!}{m-k}\\) and \\((m+k+1)! = (m+k+1)(m+k)!\\).\n\nStep 4: Apply inductive hypothesis: LHS = \\((m-k)(m+k+1) \\cdot \\prod_{i=1}^{k}(m^2+m-i^2+i)\\).\n\nStep 5: Compute \\((m-k)(m+k+1) = m^2 + m - k^2 - k = m^2+m-k(k+1)\\). For the RHS of \\(n=k+1\\): \\(\\prod_{i=1}^{k+1}(m^2+m-i^2+i) = \\left(\\prod_{i=1}^{k}(m^2+m-i^2+i)\\right) \\cdot (m^2+m-(k+1)^2+(k+1))\\). Simplify the new factor: \\(m^2+m-(k+1)^2+(k+1) = m^2+m-(k^2+2k+1)+k+1 = m^2+m-k^2-k = m^2+m-k(k+1)\\).\n\nStep 6: Thus LHS = \\(\\left(\\prod_{i=1}^{k}(m^2+m-i^2+i)\\right) \\cdot (m^2+m-k(k+1)) =\\) RHS for \\(n=k+1\\). Hence the statement holds for \\(n=k+1\\).\n\nStep 7: By mathematical induction, the identity is true for all positive integers \\(n\\) (with \\(m \\ge n\\)).\n\nFinal Answer: \\(\\frac{(m+n)!}{(m-n)!} = \\prod_{i=1}^{n}(m^2+m-i^2+i)\\)",
